Month = {AUG},
Abstract = {Coral islands like Saint Martin's have long been recognized as being
   particularly vulnerable to the consequences of climate change. Based on
   this hypothesis, the broad aim of this research work was to explore the
   environmental condition of Saint Martin's Island through a geographical
   illustration of the present status of the landform, and land use and
   land cover (LULC) characteristics. Both primary and secondary data were
   used to conduct the research work. Different types of landforms of the
   island with concerned land use characteristics have been explored
   through direct field observation. The collected data were analyzed in
   ArcGIS. Field-level elevation data were collected with global
   positioning system (GPS) during the field visit, which was used for
   ground truthing. Secondary data sources include the tidal fluctuation
   data from the BNHOC and satellite images from Google Earth Pro. The
   research found rapid changes in the LULC with a sharp increase in built
   - up areas, and the average tidal fluctuation station value increased by
   0.30 metre from 1977 to 2018. This research also found that the total
   terrestrial area is decreasing due to sea - level rise (SLR). The
   landform over 3.50 metres is relatively safer from exposure to tidal
   fluctuation. This study concludes with recommendations to assess and
   identify the inundation level due to SLR and tidal fluctuation for
   formulating an effective coastal environment conservation policy.},
