Month = {DEC},
Abstract = {Satellite technology has been used over the years by the countries the
   world over with the benefits percolating down to the society. It has
   contributed in revolutionising communications, improving natural
   resources management systems, facilitating the study of agriculture
   potential and in various fields of economic development. Satellites have
   also been used for surveillance, emergency preparedness and coordinating
   search and rescue operations on a global basis. A unique benefit of this
   technology has been realised in the area of navigation and
   radiopositioning.
   Satellite based navigation and radiopositioning was first implemented by
   the USA with the launch of TRANSIT System. TRANSIT had paved the way for
   worldwide acceptance of satellite navigation although its use, life and
   accuracy of position fixing were limited. These limitations were
   overcome with the introduction of concept of Global Positioning System
   (GPS). GPS was conceived in 1974 by the USA as a better and faster
   navigation system capable of providing three dimensional position and
   velocity information along-with precise time to all types of users
   anywhere on a 24 hours basis. GPS provides for two levels of services
   i.e. Standard Positioning Service (SPS) and Precise Positioning Service
   (PPS). The SPS is intended to provide a position fix that is accurate to
   within 100 meters on 95 percent of occasions, whereas PPS requires
   transfer from Coarse (C/A) code to the more accurate Precision (P) code,
   which allows accuracy of 16 meters on 50 percent of occasions.
   The accuracy of 100 meters available to civil users through SPS may not
   meet the requirements of applications in offshore oil exploration,
   hydrographic survey, physical oceanographic operation, fixing, collision
   avoidance, harbour approach and landing of aircraft, geophysical survey
   of remote locations and conducting search and rescue operations etc.
   This degraded accuracy can however be improved using the concept of
   Differential GPS (DGPS).
   This article deals with various issues related to the GPS technologies,
   their potential applications and system configurations available for
   these applications. An approach for design, development and
   demonstration of GPS and DGPS in Indian conditions with the active
   participation of user departments, industries and R\&D institutions
   engaged in this field has also been discussed. Since the GPS/DGPS is a
   system with potential of revolutionising the concepts in navigation and
   radiopositioning applications, it is hoped that this article will pave
   the way for promoting developmental activities for GPS/DGPS and Indian
   industries will gear up to meet the large requirements anticipated in
   near future for these.},
