@inproceedings{ WOS:000313556000115,
Author = {Testa, Giovanna},
Editor = {Schiuma, G and Spender, JC and Yigitcanlar, T},
Title = {Knowledge Transfer in Vertical Relationship. The Case Study of Val
   D'Agri Oil District},
Booktitle = {IFKAD - KCWS 2012: 7TH INTERNATIONAL FORUM ON KNOWLEDGE ASSET DYNAMICS,
   5TH KNOWLEDGE CITIES WORLD SUMMIT: KNOWLEDGE, INNOVATION AND
   SUSTAINABILITY: INTEGRATING MICRO \& MACRO PERSPECTIVES},
Year = {2012},
Pages = {2221-2246},
Note = {7th International Forum on Knowledge Asset Dynamics (IFKAD) / 5th
   Knowledge Cities World Summit (KCWS), Matera, ITALY, JUN 13-15, 2012},
Organization = {Inst Knowledge Asset Management; Queensland Univ Technol; Univ
   Basilicata; World Capital Inst},
Abstract = {The knowledge management, like a strategic resource, has gained great
   importance for business development and knowledge transfer processes
   became a key issue in allowing firms to get new sources of information.
   The study looks at the reality of industrial districts, where, normally,
   equality and fairness create the conditions upon which firms share their
   own knowledge. However, often, these contexts, in contrasts to the
   traditional Marshallian industrial district (Marshall, 1879, Becattini,
   1981), are characterized by an asymmetric power relationship among the
   parties, according to the Hub and Spoke district (Markusen, 1996). The
   case study of Val d'Agri, the most important Italian oil district, is an
   example of Hub-and-spoke District, with the dominance of a bigger firm
   (Eni) to manage all the relationship along the chain. The discovery of
   the Val d'Agri was made by ENI, in 1988.
   Purpose - Starting from the description of Val d'Agri district, our
   paper aims at mapping the local relationships, in order to define the
   way firms relate along the district value chain, with reference to both
   their position, and their own ``contractual power{''}; and to understand
   how firms position, as well as their different contractual power, affect
   knowledge transfer process within the district. Taking into account the
   ``Hub and Spoke{''} morphology, we support the idea that knowledge
   transfer is deeply affected by firms' contractual power, as well as by
   their position within the district. Explicit knowledge transfer is
   mainly linked to the development of production process; on the contrary,
   the transfer of tacit knowledge depends, above all, by the action people
   place within the district; so, human capital plays a very important role
   in transferring knowledge through imitation, work mobility and social
   interaction.
   Design/methodology/approach - We propose an empirical approach. This
   work will start providing an analysis of the main characteristics of the
   relational structure of Val d'Agri, in order to identify the main issues
   that can impact the development process of knowledge transfer. The study
   consists of two parts: in the first part, it will develop an analysis of
   the main national and international literature on the field, from both
   economic and managerial perspectives; in the second part, an empirical
   analysis will be developed. For the analysis were contacted about 100
   firms of satellite ENI industries (the biggest ones), both the same ENI.
   Were sent questionnaires for asking questions about the company
   structure, specialization, the typology of formal relationships exists
   with the leader, the company's distinctive knowledge, the existence of
   knowledge management systems.
   Originality/value - Since the importance that both industrial districts
   and knowledge transfer have for firms competition, the paper aims at
   giving a new and valuable framework useful to understand, not only the
   district dynamics, but also the way knowledge transfer may be fostered
   among all the firms related along a given value chain.
   Practical implications - The outcomes of the application puts in
   evidence the peculiarity of an oil district, because the birth of this
   form of district is closely related to land resources. In addition,
   national laws and regulations that govern the exploitation of oil in
   Italy, create positions of power within the production chain, which
   alter the relationship between the companies, compared to what happens
   in the traditional type of Marshallian districts.},
